      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-06-11T21:01:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "why is this different ?  RET_TRAP sends a signal that the process is allowed to capture.  i don\u0027t think this policy should be any different.",
      "revId": "4e0e8684d6d16557b0cb959164929c5e030f5e28",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "84af3861_35386713",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-06-12T13:55:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Right now it has to be, because RET_KILL only kills the current thread, not the entire process -- but if we\u0027re using thread-sync, we want a seccomp failure to kill the entire process. So we reset the SIGSYS disposition (in libminijail.c) and then set the return to RET_TRAP.\n\nThis, agreed, is a little brittle. While it doesn\u0027t allow a blocked syscall to go through (if the process is malicious enough to override the handler, the handler will just get called over and over again), ideally a malicious process would be killed and not just blocked.\n\nThe solution is similar as RET_LOG, since newer kernels have RET_KILL_THREAD (the old RET_KILL) and RET_KILL_PROCESS (a new value). This scaffolding can account for that as well in a follow-up CL.",
      "parentUuid": "53e433dd_f02ea861",
      "revId": "4e0e8684d6d16557b0cb959164929c5e030f5e28",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "61a03c24_8d4e172b",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 1040868
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-06-12T22:05:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "if the kernel supports it, we should be using RET_KILL_THREAD everywhere.  if we\u0027re using that, what\u0027s described here shouldn\u0027t be done.\n\nif this logic is used to workaround lack of RET_KILL_THREAD support in the kernel, then i\u0027m on board.",
      "parentUuid": "84af3861_35386713",
      "revId": "4e0e8684d6d16557b0cb959164929c5e030f5e28",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "eaa16685_95dcd903",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 17,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-06-13T13:29:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sorry, I probably wasn\u0027t fully clear.\n\nWe\u0027ve always had RET_KILL_THREAD. When Will first landed seccomp filters, there was only RET_KILL which was equivalent to RET_KILL_THREAD.\n\nWhat we want is the new RET_KILL_PROCESS so that if we enable tsync (which implies that the user knows the process is multi-threaded and moreover wants to restrict all threads), then we can kill the entire process even if only one thread calls a blocked syscall.\n\nThe SIGSYS/RET_TRAP logic is used to workaround the lack of RET_KILL_PROCESS in older kernels.",
      "parentUuid": "61a03c24_8d4e172b",
      "revId": "4e0e8684d6d16557b0cb959164929c5e030f5e28",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
