    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2ff3e0da_5cce759b",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 20,
      "author": {
        "id": 1076138
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-06-12T13:55:34Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Minijail should still support the old way of doing things, both for Linux usage and because I don\u0027t know that we\u0027ll be able to backport things as far back as 3.10/3.14. Namely, what Minijail supports and what Chrome OS kernels expose is mostly orthogonal.\n\nHaving said that, the patchset is https://www.redhat.com/archives/linux-audit/2017-February/msg00001.html, not too big, so we should attempt to backport it at least to 4.4 (since we have so many 4.4 devices) and maybe even 3.18.\n\nDetection can be done via\n\n# cat /proc/sys/kernel/seccomp/actions_avail\nkill_process kill_thread trap errno trace log allow\n\nAbsence of the file means \"OG seccomp\", presence of the file directly tells us whether log and kill_process are available.\n\nMy intention is to keep syscall_filter.{h,c} dumb (so that it\u0027s not reading anything from /proc and it\u0027s easy to unit test) and then add the above logic to libminijail.c",
      "parentUuid": "4f3af055_2f0380ee",
      "revId": "4e0e8684d6d16557b0cb959164929c5e030f5e28",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": true
    },
